		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Fitts's law</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">"fitt" redirects here. For the word used in Old English poetry, see <a href="/wiki/Beowulf" title="Beowulf">Beowulf</a>.</div>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Human-computer_interaction" title="Human-computer interaction" class="mw-redirect">human-computer interaction</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ergonomics" title="Ergonomics">ergonomics</a>, <b>Fitts's law</b> (often cited as <b>Fitts' law</b>) is a model of human movement which predicts the time required to rapidly move to a target area, as a function of the distance to the target and the size of the target.</p>
<p>Fitts's law is used to <a href="/wiki/Model_(abstract)" title="Model (abstract)" class="mw-redirect">model</a> the act of <i>pointing</i>, both in the real world (e.g., with a hand or finger) and on <a href="/wiki/Computer" title="Computer">computers</a> (e.g., with a <a href="/wiki/Computer_mouse" title="Computer mouse" class="mw-redirect">mouse</a>). It was published by <a href="/wiki/Paul_Fitts" title="Paul Fitts">Paul Fitts</a> in 1954.</p>
